    "slug": "roll-of-the-dice-cover-me-froggie-went-a-courtin",
    "status": "publish",
    "type": "post",
    "link": "https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/2021/01/26/roll-of-the-dice-cover-me-froggie-went-a-courtin/",
    "title": {
        "rendered": "Roll of the Dice/Cover Me: Froggie Went A-Courtin&#8217;"
    },
    "content": {
        "rendered": "<p>True fact: Bruce&#8217;s first solo on <em>We Shall Overcome: The Seeger Sessions</em> comes ninety seconds before the end of the album, when he finally allows himself a moment in the instrumental spotlight with his harmonica.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe class='youtube-player' width='758' height='427' src='https://www.youtube.com/embed/hmVDaczx9nU?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent' allowfullscreen='true' style='border:0;' sandbox='allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation'></iframe></span></div>\n<p>&#8220;Froggie Went A-Courtin'&#8221; is the song that finally broke through Bruce&#8217;s atypical reticence&#8211;a joyous celebration of a track and a merry way to close his 2006 Americana album.</p>\n<p>Except &#8220;Froggie Went A-Courtin'&#8221; isn&#8217;t really Americana&#8211;it predates America by over a century, dating back to Scotland in the mid-sixteenth century and possibly earlier.</p>\n<p>There&#8217;s been much debate over the folk song&#8217;s subtext, much of it speculating that it serves as commentary on the court of Queen Elizabeth I. But that&#8217;s not a settled matter, and such debates are beyond the scope of this blog.</p>\n<p>In any event, it seems clear that Bruce cared little for the political context of &#8220;Froggie Went A-Courtin&#8221; when he recorded it. It&#8217;s a familiar song (thanks to memorable recordings by Pete Seeger, Woody Guthrie, Burl Ives, Bob Dylan, and a host of others), a fun ensemble piece, and an upbeat way to close the album.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe class='youtube-player' width='758' height='427' src='https://www.youtube.com/embed/pmw0n0HTWdc?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent' allowfullscreen='true' style='border:0;' sandbox='allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation'></iframe></span></div>\n<p>There have been so many versions of &#8220;Froggie Went A-Courtin'&#8221; over the years, in fact, that over 170 verses have been collected and catalogued.</p>\n<p>Bruce seems to have taken his cue from Pete Seeger&#8217;s version (no surprise, given the inspiration for the project); although Bruce omits several of Seeger&#8217;s verses, Pete&#8217;s seems to be the first recording to include the final &#8220;cornbread&#8221; verse that also appears in Bruce&#8217;s version.</p>\n<p>How much fun is &#8220;Froggie Went A-Courtin&#8217;?&#8221;</p>\n<p>So much that Elvis Presley had a blast goofing to it at an improv studio rehearsal session.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe class='youtube-player' width='758' height='427' src='https://www.youtube.com/embed/kKtKbROMp-A?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent' allowfullscreen='true' style='border:0;' sandbox='allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation'></iframe></span></div>\n<p>And so much fun that Bruce couldn&#8217;t resist singing along with himself when he heard the playback.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe class='youtube-player' width='758' height='427' src='https://www.youtube.com/embed/rcoA9Tvgghs?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent' allowfullscreen='true' style='border:0;' sandbox='allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation'></iframe></span></div>\n<p>So why didn&#8217;t Bruce play it more often during the Seeger Sessions Tour? That I don&#8217;t know.</p>\n<p>He did play it a half-dozen times in 2006, though, and one of those (in Santander, Spain) was captured on distant video. It&#8217;s not the best quality, but it&#8217;s infectious enough to get your toes tapping.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe class='youtube-player' width='758' height='427' src='https://www.youtube.com/embed/Q2SEQyn7-FU?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent' allowfullscreen='true' style='border:0;' sandbox='allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation'></iframe></span></div>\n<p><strong>Froggie Went A-Courtin&#8217;<br />\nRecorded:</strong> March 19, 2005<br />\n<strong>Released:&nbsp;</strong><em>We Shall Overcome: The Seeger Sessions</em> (2006)<br />\n<strong>First performed:</strong> May 31, 2006 (Noblesville, IN)<br />\n<strong>Last performed:</strong> November 14, 2006 (Sheffield, England)</p>\n<p>Looking for your favorite Bruce song? Check our&nbsp;<a href=\"https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/roll-of-the-dice-album-by-album/\">full index</a>. New entries every week!</p>\n",
        "protected": false
    },
    "excerpt": {
        "rendered": "<p>One of the oldest songs from The Seeger Sessions is also the most fun. Let&#8217;s take a listen to this centuries-old folk song.</p>\n",
        "protected": false
    },
